Here are both approaches.

## 1. Register the route (AppShell.xaml.cs)

```csharp
public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
    }
}
```

## 2. Navigate from ProductListPage

**Approach A — string query parameter:**

```csharp
// In your ProductListViewModel or code-behind SelectionChanged handler
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

**Approach B — pass the full object:**

```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
}
```

## 3. Receive data with IQueryAttributable

```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _productId;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private Product _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: string parameter arrives as a string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
            ProductId = id.ToString();

        // Approach B: complex object arrives as the original type
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
            Product = p;
    }
}
```

## Key differences

| | String query param | `ShellNavigationQueryParameters` |
|---|---|---|
| **Passed via** | URL query string | Dictionary of objects |
| **Type on arrival** | `string` | Original CLR type |
| **Serialization** | You handle it (ToString) | None needed |
| **Use when** | Simple IDs, small values | Full objects, complex data |

> **Tip:** Always `await` `GoToAsync` — fire-and-forget causes silent failures. Use `ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate ...}"` in your Shell XAML so pages load on demand.
